Slideshow: Saving Gettysburg
					Newly Preserved Section of Gettysburg Battlefield
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/country-club.jpg
                    
					In March 2011, on the eve of the Civil War's 150th anniversary, the National Park Service completed its 20-year quest to attain a historic parcel of land where the Battle of Gettysburg's first major events unfolded on July 1, 1863. (Photo Credit: Civil War Trust)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Defunct Gettysburg Country Club
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/country-club-buildings.jpg
                    
					The 95-acre property, located along the Chambersburg Pike between McPherson's Ridge and Herr's Ridge, was home to the defunct Gettysburg Country Club's nine-hole golf course until 2008. It will now become part of the Gettysburg National Military Park, a 6,000-acre memorial established in 1895. (Photo Credit: Civil War Trust)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Department of the Interior Secretary Ken Salazar
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/ken-salazar.jpg
                    
					Department of the Interior Secretary Ken Salazar said of the acquisition, "With the addition of the Emanuel Harman Farm to the Gettysburg National Military Park, we are able to include another important chapter to the story that helped shape our country." (Photo Credit: Civil War Trust)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					James Lighthizer, President of the Civil War Trust
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/jim-lightizer.jpg
                    
					"This is a day that many in Gettysburg and the larger preservation community have long dreamt of," said James Lighthizer of the Civil War Trust. "In acquiring this land, known historically as the Emanuel Harman Farm, we have largely completed the protection of the first day's battlefield." (Photo Credit: Civil War Trust)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Willoughby's Run
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/willoughbys-run.jpg
                    
					The newly acquired parcel of land borders Willoughby's Run, where Confederate General James Archer and 200 of his men were captured by General Solomon Meredith's Iron Brigade. The property starts roughly to the left of this image. (Photo Credit: Civil War Trust)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					The Springs Hotel
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/springs-hotel.jpg
                    
					The land was once home to the Springs Hotel, which was built in 1869 and burned down in 1917. It was used to house visitors during the 50th anniversary of the Battle of Gettysburg in 1913. (Photo Credit: Civil War Trust)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					General George Meade at the Springs Hotel
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/meade-country-club.jpg
                    
					This postwar illustration shows General George Meade sampling the spring waters at the newly constructed Springs Hotel. (Photo Credit: Civil War Trust)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					The Josiah Benner House
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/josiah-benner-house.jpg
                    
					Preservation groups are now pursuing several other key properties related to the Battle of Gettysburg, including the historic Josiah Benner House and Farm, which served as a field hospital in the aftermath of the bloodshed. (Photo Credit: Civil War Trust)
